I prefer a drier cider, or just one that is not extremely sweet. I judge by brand as well. I prefer one that is not Redd’s or Angry Orchard, for example. I typically go for Bold Rock.

Brand name.  Always willing to try new cider, but I normally look for brand.

Brand - I try to buy VA ciders based on the fact that I grew up in VA. Flavor type, cost, label

Variety of fruits (apple, pear) and less sweet flavor profiles, more crisp.

I prefer those that are on the sweeter side with some noticeable apple flavor (prefer that taste to come at the end and linger a littleat the end). Like one that has a nice little kick to it as taste (as opppsed to flat) but not enough to throw one down and overwhelm the flavor itself.
No sweeteners; fresh, dry, fruity taste; interesting flavor combos if not plain apple cider

Taste. Not too sweet, NOT hoppy, more dry and crisp. Local is a priority after taste.
I like hard ciders in which you can really taste the fruit. I really enjoy apple and pineapple hard ciders for this reason. I also like when they’re very carbonated and on the sour side as well.

I like to go with a brand the someone recommended. I like ciders that taste like the fruit that’s advertised to be in them. I also tend to like more of a cinnamon flavor with them because I tend to drink them when it’s cooler out.
Stronger crisp apple flavor. But also economically appealing.
Flavor.  I like dry, or semi sweet cider
